metadata.name: Slanted #61
metadata.description:
Fun little game, simple rules:
- start with a randomly sized grid
- pick 2 random cells
- recursively, every cell draw itself
- then it picks two of its neighbors for the next step

Some cells are drawn multiple times, some others are never picked up, but the process it's not completely random.

metadata.name: Hashed Cities #185
metadata.description:
This token generates a deterministic set of minimal, abstract buildings of varying widths, heights, transparencies, and patterns, assembling a skyline view of your own unique imaginary city. Each city comes with its own randomized city day.

Each mint has a native setting (Day or Night) which combined with the current time of viewing influences real-time movements of celestial bodies in your mint, e.g. on a mint with the Day setting, the sun will only appear when viewed during the day. The piece will re-render every minute.

The individual strokes of this token feature some of my latest developments of an algorithm that generatively simulates the texture of print imperfections. They are randomized at each render to give it a unique character. Note that depending on the complexity of each mint, some renders may introduce a brief pause. The aesthetics are greatly inspired by plotter art of early computer artists such as 'City Painting' by Grace C. Hertlein.

Made in p5js
Created Nov 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Averno #41
metadata.description:
The work sits at the intersection of atmospheric abstraction and symbolic representation,
where generative aesthetics become a vehicle for an exploration of the perceptual threshold between form and dissolution.
Vertical structures, resembling slender shrubs or nervous filaments, construct a visual lattice that oscillates between transparency and density, suggesting a synthetic vegetation suspended between nature and algorithm.

The composition stands out for its use of digital color, with gradients that simulate traditional techniques such as pastel or watercolor, while maintaining a coherence typical of code. The generative intervention is not merely ornamental: it is a formal strategy that translates the indeterminacy of the landscape into an autonomous aesthetic language.

The sinuous shapes that emerge from below and rise upwards are not mere presences: they suggest a humanity in the making‚Äîor rather, an anthropomorphic echo generated by the system, a tension between organic mark-making and computational logic.
